teenth century and Napoleon’s campaigns of the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries to the atrocities of Mussolini and the Third Reich in the 1930s and ’40s—and sees a similar fascination with recreating the Roman past in the contemporary image. In every case—particularly that of the Nazi regime—the ruins of Rome seem to represent a mystery to be solved: how could an empire so powerful be brought so low? Hell argues that this fascination with the ruins of greatness expresses a need on the part of would-be conquerors to find something to ward off a similar demise for their particular empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aImitationxPolitical aspectszGermany. 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aNational socialism and archaeology. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aNazi empire.  aRoman empire.  abarbarian enemy.  ahistorical imaginary.  aimperial mimesis.  akatechontic sovereign.  aneo-Roman empires.  aregimes of visuality.  aruin gazer scenario.  aruined stage.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107119430 cprintz978022658805640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226588223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226588223/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  E